{"action_ids":["3909","3911","3912"],"query":"What does the evidence say about the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation or captive-release?","summary":"Sixteen studies evaluated the effects of translocating butterflies and moths to re-establish populations within their former range [3909]. Eight of these studies reported that translocated populations of adult butterflies and moth eggs persisted for 2-12 years and increased in abundance [3909]. Three other studies reported that some translocated populations persisted for 1-49 years, increased in abundance, and colonized new sites, while other populations died out within 0-7 years [3909]. One review found that 25% of translocated and released captive-bred butterfly populations survived for at least three years, while 38% died out in that time, and 8% were known to have survived for more than 10 years [3909]. Another review reported that translocated populations of large copper adults and caterpillars survived for up to 38 years but ultimately died out or required supplementation [3909]. Nineteen years after translocation, a population of large blue butterflies had similar genetic diversity to their Swedish source population [3909].

Four studies evaluated translocating butterflies and moths to establish populations outside of their known range [3911]. Two of these studies reported that populations of Gillette's checkerspot, small skipper, and marbled white butterflies translocated outside of their native range persisted and increased in abundance over eight and 28 years [3911]. However, a third study reported that a translocated population of Gillette's checkerspot died out within one year [3911]. One study found that 69 years after translocation, an introduced population of the small mountain ringlet butterfly had similar genetic diversity to its source population [3911].

Studies also found that the survival of translocated large blue caterpillars was higher in nests of the ant Myrmica sabuleti without queen ants present [3909], and the survival of translocated large copper caterpillars was higher than that of released, captive-bred caterpillars [3909]. No studies were found that evaluated the effects of introducing mated females to increase genetic diversity [3912]."}

